===Verb===
{{en-verb|abjur|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To [[renounce]] upon [[oath]]; to [[forswear]]; to [[disavow]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{reference-book|last =|first =|authorlink =|coauthors =|editor =Brown, Lesley|others =|title = The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary|origdate =|origyear = 1933|origmonth =|url =|format =|accessdate =|accessyear =|accessmonth =|edition = 5th|date =|year =2003|month =|publisher =Oxford University Press|location =Oxford, UK|language =|id =|doi =|isbn =978-0-19-860575-7|lccn =|ol =|pages =5|chapter =|chapterurl =|quote =}}</ref>
#: ''To abjure allegiance to a prince.''
#: ''To abjure the realm'' (to swear to abandon it forever).
# {{transitive|obsolete|historical}} To cause one to renounce or recant. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{transitive}} To [[reject]] with [[solemnity]]; to abandon [[forever]]; to [[repudiate]]; to [[disclaim]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''To abjure errors.''
#* '''1610''', ''[[s:The Tempest|The Tempest]]'', by [[w:William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]], act 5 scene 1
#*: But this rough magic I here '''abjure''' [...]
# {{transitive}} To abstain from; to [[avoid]]; to [[shun]].

